As you can see, other than u32_fib, most benchmarks show no difference. If the
compiler worked as intended, most of these benchmarks, which ARE formatted as
case-trees, shouldn't need to go through the interpreter at all, and, naturally,
would run much faster.

We know some cases where the compiler bails out to ALO's too early. Example:

foo = λx. !X&L=x; λ{...stuff...}

In the term above, the presentce of a DUP node between the λ and the λ-match
causes the compiler to skip fast mode, and just use an ALO for the whole body,
skipping the hot path entirely. LET's are represented as (λname.(...))(123)
or (λ{λname....})(123), which cause fallbacks too.

Your main goal is to *fundamentally redesig* HVM4's compiler to ensure that the
case-tree subset is properly compiled to efficient C functions, including
lambdas, pattern-matching, constructors, applications, operators, recursive
calls, and anything else needed to make the benchmarks above, and similar,
compute in full compiled C mode, as generically as possible.

To do so, do NOT resort to quick fixes and patches. Instead, UNDERSTAND how
interaction nets work fundamentally, reason about WHICH interactions can be
represented efficiently in native C and WHICH should fallback to ALO's, and
use THAT knowledge to redesign the compiler.

You can find the current benchmarks in:

../bench/bench (.hvm files inside that dir)

You can run them via:

~/t/dev/bench/bench.ts --timeout 3 hvmi hvmc

(Don't forget to rebuild and ensure the global `hvm` points to ./clang/main!)

